  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Prohibitive (النهي)",
      "titleArabic": "النهي",
      "content": [
        "The prohibitive form (النهي) is used to command someone NOT to do something. It is formed using لَا followed by the jussive (مجزوم) form of the mudāri' verb.",
        "Unlike the regular imperative which uses a special form, the prohibitive uses the mudāri' with its final vowel removed or changed."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Formula: لَا + مضارع مجزوم",
        "The verb takes sukūn on its final letter (or drops the نون in five verbs)",
        "لَا here is called 'lām nāhiyah' (لا الناهية) - the prohibitive لا",
        "This لَا is different from لَا النافية (negating لا)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "لَا تَذْهَبْ", "english": "Don't go! (m.)" },
        { "arabic": "لَا تَكْتُبْ", "english": "Don't write! (m.)" },
        { "arabic": "لَا تَجْلِسِي", "english": "Don't sit! (f.)" },
        { "arabic": "لَا تَخْرُجُوا", "english": "Don't exit! (pl.)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Difference from Negative Statements",
      "titleArabic": "الفرق بين النهي والنفي",
      "content": [
        "The prohibitive (لا الناهية) is different from negative statements (لا النافية). The prohibitive gives a command, while negation simply states a fact."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Prohibitive: لَا تَذْهَبْ (Don't go! - a command)",
        "Negation: لَا يَذْهَبُ (He doesn't go - a statement)",
        "In prohibitive, the verb is مجزوم (jussive)",
        "In negation, the verb stays مرفوع (indicative)"
      ]
    }
  ],
